The grant is related to the development and testing of a novel Augmented Reality WEarable Device (ARWED) for the training of the affected arm of post-stroke individuals. The system allows the user to perceive the device as part of their upper limb, hence closing the perception/action loop. Training protocols based on observational learning findings are implemented with the ARWED in order to develop it as rehabilitation training system for motor recovery of post-stroke individuals. 
The intellectual merit centers on exploiting the link between action observation and action execution. Major accomplishments include:
(i) Development of effective tools for training and physical rehabilitation of post-stroke patients;
(ii) Pilot lab testing of the effectiveness of the ARWED on priming the perception-action effect.
Preliminary results suggest that the virtual reality mirror therapy could trigger muscle activation even in patients that are more than 3 years post-stroke. This can further serve as an evidence that the time needed for recovery from stroke is not limited to one year and that additional practice can improve mobility in both the sub-acute and chronic phases following a stroke. In addition, the pilot assessment score shows a beneficial transfer of training from the affected to the unaffected limb and vise-versa.Thus, observational learning may offer greater benefits regarding transfer to Activities of Daily Living (ADLs), in comparison to robotic based stroke training.
The theoretical contributions emerging from this multidisciplinary collaborative research advance knowledge and understanding not only within the medical field, but also across science and engineering.
The broader impacts resulting from the grant include:
(i) Development of an efficient ARWED system that provides effective tools for physical rehabilitation for post-stroke individuals;
(ii) Establishment of collaborations with occupational therapists at St. Jude Centers for Rehabilitation and Wellness, Brea, CA and neurologists from UC San Diego Medical Center, CA for clinical testing;
(iii) Development of new CSUF freshman undergraduate multidisciplinary course EGGN 122 on Early Research Experiences in Biomedical Engineering and Bioengineering;
(iv) Development of a summer outreach program for 6-12 grades;
(v) Dissemination among scholars through organizing ASME IDETC M&amp;R annual symposium on Medical and Rehabilitation Robotics;
(vi) Development of new graduate level CSUF project course on Human Kinematics in Mechanical Design;
(viii) Joint industry-academia provisional patent on a related technology.




